## Migration Analysis

Your code has **3 patterns** requiring migration:

| API | Pattern | Issue in .NET 8 |
|-----|---------|-----------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement fallback | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking wait with no cancellation | Can't wake cooperatively |

There's also a **race condition bug**: multiple `Enqueue` calls can occur between `WaitOne` returning and `Reset()`, losing signals and leaving items unprocessed.

---

## Migrated Code (Idiomatic .NET 8)

The best replacement for a manual lock + queue + signal pattern is `Channel<T>`:

```csharp
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _processingTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown â€” cancellation requested
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();      // Signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // Timeout fallback
        if (_processingTask is not null)
            await _processingTask;
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

